Welsh: from a personal name derived from Greek <i>Theodōros</i>, a compound of <i>theos</i> ‘God’ + <i>dōron</i> ‘gift’, which was relatively popular in the Middle Ages because of its auspicious meaning. The name was borne by several early Christian saints. There was considerable confusion with the ancient Germanic name <i>Theodoric</i> (see   Terry  ). In Wales, the personal name <i>Theodore</i> was also adopted as an approximation to the Welsh name <i>Tewdwr</i> (see   Tudor  ). In North America, this surname has absorbed various other European cognates and their derivatives, e.g. Greek   Theodorakis  , Macedonian <b>Todorovski</b>, and Serbian <b>Todorović</b> (see   Todorovic  )."]},{"name":"Tedder","meanings":["English (Surrey): from the Middle English personal name <i>Thedere</i>, <i>Teddere</i>, which is either from the Old English personal name <i>Thēodhere</i> (from <i>thēod</i> ‘people’ + <i>here</i> ‘army’) or from the cognate ancient Germanic personal name <i>Theudher</i>, which seems to have been adopted by the Normans. Alternatively, perhaps it may be an occupational name from Middle English <i>teddere</i> ‘one who teds’, i.e. a person whose occupation was to spread mown grass for drying.","Welsh: variant of   Tudor  ."]}]},{"name":"or","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Jewish (Israeli): from Hebrew <i>or</i> ‘light’, a Hebraicized form of various original Ashkenazic surnames.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surname 柯, see   Ke   1.","Chinese: Hokkien form of the surname 胡, see   Hu   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Ke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Heng, Yong, Bin, Song, Yan, Zhi, Cheng, Chih-Ming, Chun-Yen, Fan, Fong, Gang.  Vietnamese Lan, Hai, Hoa, Le Van, Mui, Tuy.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 柯, meaning ‘bough, stalk’ in Chinese: (i) from the first element of the personal name Ke Lu (柯盧), personal name of a prince of the state of Wu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) from the first element of the placename Ke Ze (柯澤), the name of a fief (located in Shandong province) granted to an official in the state of Qi during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iii) traced back to the Qiang ethnic group in ancient western China and the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China. (iv) adopted as a surname by the Ke Ba (柯拔) family from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ).","Chinese: variant of   Ge  ."]}]},{"name":"Mali","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Màiri ."],"variants":[{"name":"Màiri","meanings":["Gaelic equivalent of <b>Mary</b> ."]},{"name":"Mary","meanings":["From Old French <i>Marie</i>.  See  <b>Mary</b>   ."]}]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["1  ‘Sharp blade’.","2  ‘Wind’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mali ferch Tudor or Tewdwdwr was born in 1400, in Abergele, Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom, her father, Tudur ab Ieuan \"Gôch\", was 27 and her mother, Mrs. Tudur ab Ieuan Goch, was 23. She had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"1400–":"1400–Surnud","1400–Female":"1400–Surnud","1501–Male":"1501–Surnud","1426–Female":"1426–Surnud","1435–Male":"1435–Surnud","1438–Male":"1438–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1374–Male":"1374–Surnud","1378–Female":"1378–Surnud","1426":"1426","1435":"1435","1501":"1501","1400":"1400","1378":"1378","1374":"1374","1438":"1438","of, Plas Ystiwart, Abergele, Denbighshire, Wales":"Abergele, Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1400–":"1400–Kuollut","1400–Female":